02/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Cultural performances are a crucial way of seeking political mobilisation in contemporary postcolonial countries. This project identifies and analyses the similarities and differences between the political Left and the political Right in India when it comes to using cultural performances as political tools. This focus on actors lying on two opposing ends of the political spectrum allows a new and rich conceptualisation of politics of mass mobilisation through culture, a conceptualisation that sees politics as performance and culture as constitutive and contested. The main emphasis for the Left is on raising awareness and creating consciousness of contradictions within the society. On the other hand, the political Right (Hindu nationalism) focuses on appropriating culture as a pregiven symbol that draws a clear line between the insider-outsider and assures its constituency that the enemy is outside. This comparative interdisciplinary study of cultural performances as political tools by the Left and the Right in the largest democracy in the world, in a country predicted to be a great power in the near future, is unprecedented, timely, and of significance beyond the geographical location.
